Decade variable resistor 0 - 10Mohm* in increments of 1ohm with a laser cut enclosure using moderately cheap and easily sourceable components. Total cost for the parts orders looks to be just under $40 plus acrylic ($10 for a 24"x18" at Lowe's), but this doesn't take into account the fact that, e.g, while you are ordering 100 bolts, you are only using 12. Real cost is probably closer to $15. The soldering is rather tightly packed, so proceed at your own risk. A word of warning: I designed this mostly for myself, so don't assume that everything will be perfect. I may also refine a couple things in the coming weeks. A note about resistor tolerances: I'm using 1% resistors. I wanted something better than the really cheap and common 5% resistors, but much better than 1% costs too much. Also, the switches themselves add resistance and some variance. The tolerances don't add like some people worry for setups like this - any resistance I can dial in will be within 1% of the number on the switches - in theory. The switches add a couple ohms (1.5ish) to the box overall, so the low values will be more imperfect than the high values. Also, it's best practice that once you tune a circuit with a box like this, you remove the box then measure the resistance instead of relying on the readout. If you just want a decade resistor instead of taking the time to do it this way, Sparkfun has a kit for $30 that'll go from 0-1M with 10ohm increments. I like mine better. *Yes, I'm lying to you. It actually only goes up to 9,999,999 ohms.

• 2mm acrylic (~100x220mm)
  • M2.5 by 8mm machine screws x12
  • M2.5 hex nuts x12
  • 10-digit decimal switches x7
  • Dual banana plug jack x1
  • 1% resistors 9 each of 1, 10, 100, 1k, 10k, 100k, 1M

• Order the parts. I've provided links to my sources, but there are probably other suppliers that'll work just as well, but if your parts are a different size, they probably won't fit my designs.
  • Solder 9 resistors to each decimal switch like this. For the one's switch, be careful about where the resistors are as this switch is butted against the box's right side wall.* Check proper function of all 7 blobs.
  • Solder all 7 switch/resistor blobs together.
  • Cut the box from 2mm acrylic (or wood?). The t-slots are a little picky, so something other than 2mm would take a redesign. I suggest a test cut in cardstock to check the fit of everything.
  • Mount the banana plug jack to the top panel, and insert the decade switch block into the panel. Secure with a line of hot glue on the underside.
  • Solder the input and the output of the decade resistor chain to the banana plug jack.
  • Loosely assemble the side panels.
  • Assemble the top panel and bottom panel on to the side panel assembly.
  • After everything fits, tighten all screws.
  • Rejoice!

*Something that I would possibly suggest changing with my design is that instead of having the banana plugs to the left of the switches, assemble the box with the banana plugs to the right of the switches. This should take care of the problem with the resistors getting in the way on the one's switch.

The SVG file is the one to cut. It has all 6 panels together. Units should be mm.   
The DXFs are face exports from Autodesk Inventor. Inkscape doesn't like them for some reason, and if anyone can manage to successfully export DXFs from Inventor and get them to open in Inkscape, PLEASE let me know. I can't get straight lines to show up - only curves.   
The IPTs are the Inventor files. I have the 2013 student version. The t-slots are a custom iFeature, so if that didn't export properly enough for you to edit the parts, let me know.

This is the remixed version of the dual extruder file. I don't have any dual extruder printer, so I take some effort to split everything out. It's lots of work to print them part by part but I'm sure the result is worth the effort.

Some of the file is not properly aligned flat on printer table since I just export the original file from CAD. Please align them before you print. Please refer to the picture of my printed minion for clearer reference. Most of the parts can be printed without support except the body. It'll need a little support for the hands. The most hard part is the hair since they are so small and they are 12 of them that need to be aligned flat. Good luck printing and assembling the minion! UPDATE (27 Dec 2014)
For those who are using CURA for slicing, please enable the Fix Horrible Type B in your Expert Setting while printing the BODY.stl. This is because that particular part has overlapping mesh so the Type B will stitch them together properly. Otherwise you'll find a disturbing hole at the side of the minion's body.

Not sure if this type of spice bottle is common outside of Northern Europe, but here you have it anyway... This is model for the white inner cap.
Those spice bottles/jars are tempting to re-use because you can get refillls in cheap bags, however the inner caps get lost, worn out or are just wrong type for the spice you're refilling - ie. it could be one with small holes for ground pepper when you fill it with whole peppers, or vice versa.
3D printing those inner caps is a perfect solution. Note though that this is work in progress, the inner cap doesn't currently have any holes in it! It was difficult enough to get the fit right, and the model clean, and I thought people would want to experiment with their own hole patterns etc. so here it is while I get around to working on the holes myself :)
The fit is intentionally really, really snug, but as can be seen in the image works at least for me in 0.1mm PLA without support. It might be necessary to scale it up by 1% or something for some printers.

Here are cat coasters 13 through 16 of the coasters based on the 17 plane groups. See Cat Coasters 01,02 and 03 - things 54736, 56813 and 58639. The four plane groups are: p3, p31m, p3m1, and p6. All of these groups contain three fold rotation axes. p6 also has six fold rotation axes. P3 and P6 have only rotational symmetry while p3m1 and p31m contain combinations of reflection and glide lines. The four sets of files for dual extrusion are: cat_coasters_p3.stl and cat_decorations_p3.stl
cat_coasters_p31m.stl and cat_decorations_p31m.stl
cat_coasters_p3m1.stl and cat_decorations_p3m1.stl
cat_coasters_p6.stl and cat_decorations_p6.stl Cat_coasters_04 scad created the stl files and the images are in coasters_dxf_04.zip

The coasters are 110 mm in diameter and should be constructed directly on the build surface.   I used one shell and ten percent infill and the coasters printed in about two hours.
The coasters can be used as teaching aids.  Pdf files that show some of the symmetry elements are included in coasters_dxf_04.zip.  Reflection lines are shown in red and glide lines in blue.

description.text:
My RaspPi Case - acrylic laser cut design http://www.led-genial.de/Plexiglas-Gehaeuse-fuer-Raspberry-Pi Deutsch unten ! This great design allows the use of several parts and can be assembled easily. Simultaneously there is no danger to break it.
The striking advantage of this design is the possibility to use colored plexiglass or acrylic.
With the popular kits for hobbyists that you can stick together the only material which can be used is rolled XT. Otherwise it will break because of the high tolerances regarding the thickness that are used by the system itself—especially when the case is dissembled and reassembled very often.
Unfortunately, XT is only available in very few colors and does not allow the user to make use of significantly different degrees of thickness.
So it is a lot cleverer to only manufacture the lids in GS (cast) while all of the side parts are made of XT (rolled).
For an easy assembly use 20mm spacers and M3 6mm screws.
By the way, it is not possible to assemble the case the wrong way. Its parts only fit with the correct orientation. It cannot be assembled in a mirror-inverted way, for example. Simple and awesome!
Following the assembly the case is astoundingly stable in spite of the quartering.
Have fun assembling your personal yin and yang case! Und hier in Deutsch: Das tolle Design, was Mehrteiligkeit erlaubt und leicht montierbar ist, dabei keinerlei Bruchgefahr.
Der absolute Vorteil dieses Designs ist die Verwendbarkeit von farbigen Plexiglas bzw. Acryl. Bei den bekannten „zusammensteckbaren“ Bastelsätzen muss ausschließlich gewalztes XT verwendet werden, ansonsten kommt es aufgrund der systembedingten hohen Toleranzen der Dicke, immer wieder zu Bruch. Gerade wenn öfter mal das Gehäuse demontiert/montiert wird. Leider gibt es XT (sehr geringe Toleranzen in der Dicke) nur in wenigen Einfärbungen. Daher ist es viel cleverer nur die Deckel in GS (gegossen) zu produzieren. Die Seitenteile sind alle XT (gewalzt). Für die einfache Montierbarkeit 20mm Spacer + M3 6mm Schrauben. NIE WIEDER BRUCH!
Ach - und es ist nicht möglich falsch zu montieren, die Teile passen nur in der korrekten Ausrichtung. Keine nervige, spiegelverkehrtes Zusammensetzen möglich. Einfach und klasse! Zum Schluss noch der Hinweis, nach Montage ist das Gehäuse trotz der Vierteilung verblüffend stabil - also keine Hemmungen - viel Spaß beim Nachbau!

Now the dark season is welcome! You can only play the game in the dark.
This is a stereographic projection of the famous game Mill (also known as Nine Man Morris, Mill, Mills, The Mill Game, Merels, Merrills, Merelles, Marelles, Morelles and Ninepenny Marl).
When you place a light on top of the projection body, the shadows which are created will build a game plate
Read more in the instructions! Watch a short video at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x65ZbuQRLOA

• You will always need to print the projection-printable.stl file. It is printable without support and takes about 2 hours to print with a layer height of 0.3 mm. It is based on http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:295281. The image array was created with http://customizer.makerbot.com/image_array.
  • If you want to play in a more comfortable way, you can print out the additional aufsatz.stl. You can place an LED trough the hole (not the body, only the wires) and put a battery holder on top of it. If there is interest, I'll draw a circuit plan. Hook up a resistor between 10 Ohm and 20 Ohm in series to the battery and LED to limit the current and increase the lifetime of the LED. You should remove the round head of the LED to improve the angle of radiation. Alternatively, you can use a torch (of you smartphone). Torches with multiple LEDs won't work since they will produce multiple shadows.

title: Simple Mobius gimbal for X520 frame

description.text:
Update 20.02.2015:
New version with a different vibration damping approach here:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:691553

Update 12.02.2015:
I added an "extended" version of both the arm and Mobius mount.
I realized that when installing a filter lens in front of the mobius, the weight of the filter is too much to balance the camera anymore. Now it can be slid further left and back to allow more adjustments.

Update 23.01.2015:
Mobius carrier updated again. Less support again, strengthened the top of the upper screw slit a bit, added a gap for certain larger USB plugs.
Camera is now meant to be slid into it straight (as opposed to angled), side supports are lengthened to give more hold for the camera and less chance to break after a few insertions. Front springy "nubs" were reduced in height to allow straight sliding.

Update 22.01.2015:
Updated the Mobius carrier to need less support when printing and slightly sturdier clips.

Update 17.01.2015:
Finally was able to try it out. I left the cam running while doing the initial setup of my rebuilt quadcopter.
Video is here: http://youtu.be/FjgQQuY5g3Q
This is what the copter does when running auto tune (not my video!):
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zE-NJUlXxe8

Very simple gimbal that I made to fit the X520 "Alien" type frame. Works with the basic cheap china gimbal motors, 4x M3 back and 4x M2 front mounting holes. 9mm anti vibration balls needed.
Adjustable screw slots to balance the camera perfectly.

title: Dr Boo's Mini Kossel Endstop for SS5 microswitch

description.text: Here's my take on an end-stop for 1515 beam on Mini Kossel printers. I wanted something that encapsulated the micro-switch, but also that put the mounting screw on the outside of the beam. The SS5 micro-switch slides into the hole, and you can put a couple of screws through the holes to secure it. The inner bumps don't go very deep so you can have wiring inside your 1515 channels passing through this end-stop. Of course it can be mounted either way (up or down), as per the original.

These stackable comb modules can be used to vegetate walls.
They're mounted with magnets - so works only if your wall is of Metal :)
But they can also just be stacked without magnets. There are 3 different types: type A, B and C The type A comb modules have overflow wholes that drain excessive water to the modules below. The bottom modules don't have any drain wholes and are the end point of exceeding water. The type B modules don't have drain wholes at all and can be mounted individually at any hight of your wall without being stacked - with any distance from the next module. Type C modules don't have bolts and therefore not space between the modules and the wall. There are also two magentic distance bolts for type A and type B comb modules. I know, it's complicated. Type A bolts can be used with one small 5x20mm magnet and are strong enough to hold the comb modules, if your bottom modules are standing on ground or on a table. If you want to hang your combs at any hight of the wall, use Type B bolts. These fit 2 larger magnets of 7x30mm dimension and can hold your plant anywhere. Drill holes into the bolts in order to screw or nail it to your wall. On one of the pictures you can see a test setup on a table with the drip irrigation system called Blumat (the pic with the hoses). That's very sexy but not needed. You can irrigate also with the watering can the old fashioned way. If irrigated by hand and not by a dripping system, the combs must be printed 100% water tight. Producing really water tight objects needs some testing with your printer and slicer. Slow down printing of the outermost perimeter by 50% for watertight printing. If found out that simpliy3D has a function called multiprocessing. This allows repeated changes of print settings at any layer height, so that corners become water tight too. inspired by www.hydroplant.ch

title: DSLR Camera 15mm Rails Platform
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I've been doing development on my motion control rig for a few years now. After selling my primary camera for the rig (Sony F3), I only had my Nikon DSLR left to test the rig with. Since I didn't have a way to mount the required focus and zoom motors, or even a way to attach the camera to the rig at all, I made a complete camera platform 100% 3D printed.
I looked on this site for anything that would work that someone else had already made but I couldn't find anything that worked exactly how I needed it to, so I modeled everything from scratch in OpenSCAD. I'm not an OpenSCAD expert and the code shows it, so I won't be posting the source files. If you want them, just ask and I'll send them to you.
Also keep in mind that I modeled the bottom plate to fit directly into the Bogen tripod quick release plate. This makes the rig much simpler. If you need it to fit your tripod plate, just design a new bottom or put holes in my bottom plate and attach your tripod adapter.
Obviously there is a bit of risk in creating a part like this and putting $5k worth of camera equipment on it. I'm confident that the parts I printed are up to task and I'm not too worried about breaking my camera, but use at your own risk.
Also, the rig pictured is using my 15mm Stepper Motor Rail Mounts too. That part has its own page and you can get the STL for that there.
Lastly, the actual 15mm rods are standard rods. They are not printed. I get mine from Filmtools.

You'll need some 1/4-20 Panhead screws for the platforms to attach to the vertical posts. I get mine from home depot. I can probably find the exact SKU for you if you need it. I sized the holes in the vertical rails just perfectly so they can be tapped with a 1/4-20 tap. Sorry if you don't have a tap, just go buy one. They're not that expensive. Just get a good grip on the rod and tap it, pretty easy. 
You'll need some 1/4-20 hex nuts and bolts too. These are used to fix the rail holders to the vertical posts and also for the rail holders to grip the rails.
The camera is held on the platform with a thumb bolt. The rod blocks are fixed to the vertical rods with a super extended thumb bolt. The 15mm rails are using a  shallow extended thumb bolt. These are all essentially the same thumb bolt with different depths to fit the purpose.
The lens support is very specific and it was made to fit my 24-70mm Nikon. Your lens probably needs a support with a different diameter. If you get the OpenSCAD source from me, you can probably figure it out.
I am aware that the bolt hole in the rail holders is slightly off-center. I can't figure out why but it still works fine. If there is an OpenSCAD expert who thinks they can unravel my code and figure it out, please do.
If you make one, post a picture of your rig so I can check it out. Good luck!

My daughter's Barbie house was lacking certain 'facilities', so I decided to design and print them. The toilet has a separately articulated seat and lid, and should in principle come together without extra hardware: the seat attaches to the base, and the lid to the seat. However, I ended up securing the lid to the seat with small screws for a better fit.
I printed the faucet separately from the sink body and super-glued it afterwards (in order to avoid using supports).
The toilet paper roll was printed separately from its holder and slides on afterwards.
Everything is sized to fit in reasonably well with standard Barbie dolls.

The included OpenSCAD file should be modular enough to extract printable sub-assemblies. I also included STL files for most.
I printed everything on a Rostock-style delta FDM printer, no supports should be necessary (provided the faucet is done separately).

description.text:
This is the carriage for a personalised Mendel90 currently under construction. The smaller carriage will accept a multi-material bowden extruder or perhaps a smaller direct drive.
The flexors connecting to the third bearing mount are shorter than they should be. But remodelling has been postponed until I learn openSCAD. Meanwhile the corresponding 40mm fan duct is on the drawing board and will be published soon.

The carriage is designed to accept LM8UU bearings, GT2 and T5 timing belts.
UPDATE: A trapped nut pocket (for the belt tensioner) is in the wrong place. If you still want to make use of the carriage, I recommend using a soldering Iron to melt a nut into the wall at the right place on the part. I will correct the file as soon as I can.
UPDATE 29/03/13: Trapped nut now on the correct side. Third mounting bolt socket included (consider it's position above the X axis bars when installing). A version for T5 timing belts has also been added.
This is a plate to put on the glasses. This clip part is small wide. It will not put on a cell frame. When there are a lot of requests, I make that for a cell frame.

title: Motorcycle Daytime Running Lights (DRL) 18mm LED Mounts

description.text: These generic and specific mounts work with common 18mm 12V 3W LED daytime running lights seen on some new cars. The mounts should be printed with medium to high density so they are strong and mounting holes can be drilled safely. You can drill and mount these into existing fairing mounting holes. The DRL LED’s can be found individually or in packs from Amazon and eBay. They are inexpensive, have aluminum housings, and they are waterproof. I’ve received a few that needed a little additional RTV where the wire enters the housing to ensure a strong waterproof bond but otherwise these work great. Check out my video with 2 mounted under the headlight of my Ninja 650R. The lights and no-solder wire kits are available at dimensionbx.com.
Medium resolution with medium-high density recommended
